    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-14T00:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-14T00:30:00-05:00" n="857"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d857">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">789.00/7–1454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Afghanistan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Little</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d857fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to
                        Karachi, New Delhi, London, Moscow, and Jidda.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kabul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-14T10:00:00+04:30"
                            >July 14,1954—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>16. Embassy telegram 11, July 10.<note n="2" xml:id="d857fn2">
                        <ref target="#d856">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> Embassy informed by usually reliable sources <gloss
                        target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> Pushtunistan agitation and plebiscite demand
                        <pb facs="0364" n="1414" xml:id="pg_1414"/> reported <gloss
                        target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> now receiving active support India and
                    probably Soviet Union. <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName>’s talks with
                    Chou En-lai<note n="3" xml:id="d857fn3">Prime Minister Chou En-lai met with
                        Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> in New Delhi from
                        June 26 to June 28, 1954. A text of the communiqué issued after their talks
                        is printed in Royal Institute of International Affairs, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Documents on International Affairs, 1954</hi>, pp. 313–314.</note>
                    believed impressed <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> giving prestige and
                    weight Indian representation.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> reportedly has urgently stressed following
                    points.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Afghan fear Soviet Union needless as India will ensure Soviet observance
                        Afghan-Soviet 1921 friendship pact.<note n="4" xml:id="d857fn4">The
                            Afghan-Soviet Treaty of Friendship of Feb. 28, 1921 is printed in <hi
                                rend="italic">A Collection of Treaties, Engagements, and Sanads
                                Relating to India and Neighboring Countries</hi>, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">xiii</hi>, pp. cxcvii–cxcix.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> must take advantage soon Indian
                        friendship offer and presumably join Asian neutralist bloc or find herself
                        alone since US cannot offer comparable friendship owing Pakistan alliance
                        and India cannot be held responsible Soviet action should <gloss
                            target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> join US-sponsored alliance.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> should make Pushtunistan international
                        issue (presumably UN) and not mere dispute between two Muslim powers. If so
                        handled <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> assures Afghanistan support
                        India, Soviet bloc and unnamed members “Asia bloc”.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Little</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
